{
  "doc_id": "22416",
  "text": "In conclusion, our findings show impaired sweet, salty, bitter, umami and fat taste in IBD patients, but increased sour taste. Reductions in sweet, umami, and fat perception may contribute to increased consumption of foods rich in sugar, fat and protein by IBD patients and possibly excess weight gain in some of these individuals [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . Elevated sour taste in IBD patients may interfere with food enjoyment and may represent a separate quality of life issue in this disease.",
